File: platform/browser-extension/src/network-capture.ts

The stale request pruning logic is at lines 190-194, inside the Network.requestWillBeSent handler:
```
const cutoff = now - PENDING_REQUEST_TTL_MS;
for (const [rid, ts] of state.requestIdToRequest) {
  if (ts < cutoff) state.requestIdToRequest.delete(rid);
}
```

This only runs when a new request arrives. If no requests come in (idle capture), stale entries from responseReceived (line 237) that never got loadingFinished sit forever.

Fix: Add an intervalId field to CaptureState (line 77-93). In startCapture (line 381), start a setInterval that calls the same pruning logic. In stopCapture (line 420), clearInterval it.

Keep the existing pruning in requestWillBeSent as well — it's a good optimization for active captures. The interval is a safety net for idle periods.

Pruning interval suggestion: 30_000ms (30 seconds). Use the same PENDING_REQUEST_TTL_MS (60_000ms) as the cutoff.

Test file: platform/browser-extension/src/network-capture.test.ts (it already exists). Use vi.useFakeTimers to test that advancing the timer prunes entries.
